This project aims to contribute to socio-economic development in Burkina Faso and to curb irregular migration through fighting poverty and promoting employment. The project aims to provide young people, including vulnerable groups such as women and people with disabilities, with skills that respond to labour market needs and to support entrepreneurial activities. An awareness campaign on the risks of irregular migration that will involve the Burkinabe diaspora will also be conducted.

The overall objective of the proposed project is to contribute to improving police accountability and security for the population of Mbuji-Mayi through the reinforcement of community policing precepts.
The overall goal of this project is to contribute to Indonesia's efforts to reduce vulnerability and enhance the resilience of communities to natural disasters.

The project will address the urgent needs of water and sanitation service delivery in rural and peri-urban areas affected by recurrent drought and waterborne diseases such as acute watery diarrhea and cholera.

Through multiple grant activities, the program objective seeks to help extend the writ of the Government of Pakistan (GOP) and increase access to unbiased, public information about GOP policies.

The Middle East Response (MER) initiative is an innovative approach thatwill provide essential HIV, TB, and malaria services to eligible countrypopulations in Syria, Yemen and Syrian refugees in Jordan and Lebanon. This will be done through one regional grant management platform with the aim of improving responsiveness to the three diseases in the contextof emergencies in the aforementioned countries. The grant will consolidate current national grants in Syria, Yemen and the Emergency Fund Grant in Jordan and Lebanon. The scope of interventions under the grant was tailored to reflect the protracted conflict and refugee crisisin the abovementioned countries in consultation with technical partners.The grant will be managed by IOM through an integrated grant management platform, based in Amman, Jordan as IOM will capitalize on its country missions in the region to oversee grant implementation on the grounds, including in hard to reach areas of Yemen and Syria.

The Middle East Response (MER) Phase 2 is a multi-country three-year project supported by the Global Fund aiming to deliver continuum of care in challenging operating environments, through provision of essential HIV, tuberculosis and malaria services which is essentially the continuation of its preceding project, MER Phase 1 which was implemented in 2017-2018. The interventions are planned towards addressing the needs of general populations with focus on vulnerable groups including refugees, migrants and internally displaced people and people in hard-to-reach areas in Syria, Yemen and Iraq. It also includes Syrian refugees, migrants and vulnerable populations in Jordan and Lebanon where the latter is expanded to Palestine refugees.

As part of IOM's response to the needs of Rohingya population in Cox's Bazaar, IOM is adopting an integrated approach to support life-saving and sustaining assistance as well as early recovery activities. The overarching priorities under this project include the respect and upholding of protection needs of the Rohingya, but also improvement of quality and access to services. IOM will continue to provide support to the most vulnerable host community members and mitigate the impact of the refugee influx on the environment in order to strengthen social cohesion.

As outward migration in Cambodia continues to increase, its impact on the children and families of migrant workers inclusive of health, remains largely unknown. Concerns center on how separation from parents may affect children's nutritional, behavioral and psychological development and if furthermore the trends in migration have linkages to the increased placement of children in Residential Care Institutions (RCI) settings. In this regard a two phase project is proposed that aims to research the issue of left behind children and families in Cambodia. The first phase will focus on piloting and capacity building activities whilst phase two will consist of a community-based cross-sectional household survey among left-behind migrant worker families and qualitative study components to explore left-behind migrant children in child care institutions inclusive of children's perception of parental migration, child health status and parenting issues of migrant family households. The final outcome of the project will be to present the findings and recommendations via a country report to the Royal Government of Cambodia and Civil Society in Cambodia to assist with culturally appropriate interventions and national policy development.
